  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.3190" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <p>Do not be angry, or think that I claim to be a scientific man like you. If <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.837">Basque</ref>
          <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">ozka</hi> is from <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">absecare</hi> I should like to find an old or dialectal form <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">auzka</hi> - would English <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">notch</hi> be from <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">hoche</hi>? compare <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">newt</hi> from “an <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">ewt</hi>” or “<hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">eft</hi>”! I shall reply to <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2188">
Meyer</persName> and quote your remarks on this word and <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">silvaticus</hi> – about the latter you support me, for referring to <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">salvai</hi> in <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5796">Girard de Roussillon</persName>, which he said in class coud not be explained, I told him the <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.837">Basque</ref> had received it in that form. He wrote back that <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">salvai</hi> or <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">salbai</hi> coud only come from <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">salvadius</hi>, which never I think existed! I must say that many leading philologists seem to <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
enslave</hi> themselves to <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">imagined</hi> hard and fast rules, whereas languages have been corrupted, and misshapen, by popular <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">ignorance</hi>
          <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">lawlessness</hi> and <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">caprice</hi> – What law makes <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">
finem</hi> masculine in <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.779">
Spanish</ref> but feminine in Gaulish? You seem to make <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">passiv</hi> and<hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none"> intransitive</hi> as applied to the Basque verb the reverse of synonymous. What think you of my supplement? My poverty affects my health and hinders my studies.</p>
        <closer>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1402">E. S. Dodgson.</persName>
          </signed>
        </closer>
        <postscript>
          <p>
            <note n="1" place="foot" type="editorial">Notiz am linken Rand.</note> Paris, 31 January 1893. To D<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.109">H. Schuchardt.</persName>
          </p>
          <p>
            <note n="2" place="foot" type="editorial">Notiz am rechten Rand.</note>I will write to <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2001">
Larrieu</persName> for the price.</p>
        </postscript>
